# HTML File Naming

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL follow consistent naming conventions.

## File Extension

All HTML files SHALL use the `.html` file extension.

## Naming Convention

All HTML files SHALL use lowercase letters and hyphens (kebab-case):

- File names SHALL be lowercase
- Words SHALL be separated by hyphens (`-`)
- File names SHALL NOT contain spaces
- File names SHALL NOT contain underscores (except when required by framework conventions)
- File names SHALL NOT contain special characters except hyphens

## Examples

Valid file names:

- `index.html`
- `user-profile.html`
- `contact-form.html`
- `about-us.html`
- `product-detail-page.html`

Invalid file names:

- `Index.html` (uppercase)
- `user_profile.html` (underscore)
- `contact form.html` (space)
- `aboutUs.html` (camelCase)
- `product@detail.html` (special character)

## Directory Structure

HTML files SHOULD be organized in a logical directory structure:

- Root level: `index.html`
- Pages: `pages/` or similar directory
- Components: `components/` or `partials/` (for template systems)
- Templates: `templates/` (for template engine files)

## Template Files

Template files (Jinja2, Handlebars, etc.) MAY use framework-specific extensions:

- Jinja2: `.jinja` or `.html`
- Handlebars: `.hbs` or `.handlebars`
- Mustache: `.mustache`

However, when possible, `.html` extension SHOULD be used for consistency.

## Special Files

Common HTML file names:

- `index.html` - Default page for a directory
- `404.html` - Error page (may be required by hosting)
- `robots.txt` - Not HTML, but may be in HTML directory

## File Name Length

File names SHOULD be descriptive but concise:

- Avoid overly long file names
- Use abbreviations when commonly understood
- Balance descriptiveness with readability

## Case Sensitivity

File names SHALL be lowercase to avoid case-sensitivity issues across different operating systems and web servers.
